cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "The Compiler as Oracle: Reliable LLM-Based Architecture Modeling via a Typed Internal DSL"
type: article
authors:
  - family-names: Betchvaia
    given-names: Irakli
    affiliation: kUML Project
    email: irakli@betchvaia.de
    website: "https://betchvaia.de"
abstract: >-
  Large language models (LLMs) are increasingly used to generate software
  architecture models from natural-language descriptions, typically
  targeting untyped external DSLs such as PlantUML or Mermaid. Because these
  formats defer all validation to render time, LLM outputs frequently
  contain hallucinated references, dangling associations, and semantically
  inconsistent structures that are silently rendered or fail with
  uninformative parse errors. We propose a Generate-Compile-Repair (GCR)
  framework, an instance of a general method we call Typed Domain Grounding,
  in which the target language is a statically typed internal DSL -- kUML,
  embedded in Kotlin -- and the Kotlin compiler serves as a deterministic,
  zero-cost validation oracle. A full run over a 50-task benchmark comparing
  kUML, PlantUML, and Mermaid shows kUML + GCR achieves the highest semantic
  fidelity and lowest hallucination rate of the three.
keywords:
  - domain-specific languages
  - large language models
  - software architecture
  - model-driven engineering
  - self-repair
  - typed domain grounding
  - kUML
license: CC-BY-4.0
